The third planet from the sun, Earth, is the largest of the Inner circle. The only planet known to currently contain liquid water, Earth’s atmosphere protects the planet from dangerous radiation and helps keep the sunlight and warmth in. It’s proximity from the Sun (not too far or too close) keeps Earth from becoming overheated, or from becoming too cold. Like the other planets of the Inner circle, Earth has a rocky surface with mountains and canyons, along with a heavy metal core. Earth’s atmosphere contains water vapor, which helps moderate it’s temperatures. Earth’s moon is comprised of various rocks and minerals
Water covers roughly 71% of the Earth’s surface, and most of that is salt water. The air in Earth’s atmosphere is approximately 78% nitrogen and 21% oxygen. Nowhere else in the solar system is there an atmosphere loaded with free oxygen, which is vital to one of the most unique features of the planet Earth: life.
While extra-terrestrial (or, alien) life has long been theorized, we have yet to discover any life past the planet Earth. Earth boasts several million species of life, living in habitats ranging from the bottom of the ocean to the highest mountains. Life outside of Earth is very possible, but as it stands, none have been found.
